                                <h1 style="font-family: 'Archivo Black', sans-serif; margin: 0; padding: 0;">SNITCHES</h1>

                                <p style="margin: 0; padding: 0;">
                                    Snitches are a handy tool for both defensive and agressive playstyles.
                                </p>

                                <p style="margin-top: 16px;">
                                    In the case of defense, Snitches hold logs that last for up to 3 days. During this time it will track
                                    events that happen within a <b>16 block radius</b> of it. These events include:
                                    Connections, Disconnections, Spottings, Block Breaking, Block Placing, Block Interactions
                                    and Player Deaths. When these events are logged initially, every player with the proper
                                    permissions on your network can see exactly where the spotted player is in their chat. This is extremely
                                    handy if you want to protect your base and need to be notified that a player may be attacking it.
                                </p>

                                <p style="margin-top: 16px;">
                                    When it comes to using Snitches offensively, they are a great tool for tracking down players. If you have a
                                    general idea of where to look for players but don't know exactly or when, placing a Snitch allows you to watch
                                    an area without actually being there.
                                </p>

                                <p style="margin-top: 16px; margin-bottom: 0; padding: 0;">To create a Snitch, type</p>
                                <p style="margin-bottom: 0; padding: 0;"><kbd>/snitch create &lt;network&gt; &lt;location description&gt;</kbd></p>
                                <p>while looking at a Jukebox.</p>
                            </div>
                            
                            <div class="col-sm">
                                <div class="embed-responsive embed-responsive-16by9">
                                    <iframe class="embed-responsive-item" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/1zJGXlTuMz8" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>
                                </div>

                                <h5 style="margin-top: 8px;">Commands</h5>
                                <p style="font-size: 0.8rem;"><kbd>/snitch create &lt;network&gt; &lt;location description&gt;</kbd> - Create a Snitch</p>
                                <p style="font-size: 0.8rem;"><kbd>/snitch log</kbd> - View the logs for a Snitch block you are looking at</p>
                                <p style="font-size: 0.8rem;"><kbd>/snitch clear</kbd> - Clear the logs for a Snitch block you are looking at</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="tab-pane fade" id="acid" role="tabpanel">
                        <div class="row">
                            <div class="col-sm">
                                <img src="/images/acid.png" style="max-width: 100%;">
                                <h1 style="font-family: 'Archivo Black', sans-serif; margin: 0; padding: 0;">ACID</h1>

                                <p style="margin: 0; padding: 0;">
                                    Acid Blocks will tick damage to all fortified blocks within a <b>3x3x3</b> radius of the Acid Block.
                                    Acid Blocks can be stacked together, dealing multiple points of damage per tick.
                                </p>

                                <br>

                                <p style="margin: 0; padding: 0;">
                                    Type <kbd>/acid create &lt;network&gt;</kbd> while looking at a Gold Block to create a new Acid Block.
                                    Once the Acid Block matures it will begin damaging all fortified blocks within its range.
                                </p>

                                <br>

                                <p style="margin: 0; padding: 0;">
                                    <b>Note:</b> Acid Blocks will automatically expire after 3 days.
                                </p>
                            </div>

                            <div class="col-sm">
                                <div class="embed-responsive embed-responsive-16by9">
                                    <iframe class="embed-responsive-item" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/nZnl4KR7nWk" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>
                                </div>

                                <h5 style="margin-top: 8px;">Commands</h5>
                                <p style="font-size: 0.8rem;"><kbd>/acid create &lt;network&gt;</kbd> - Create an Acid Block</p>
                                <p style="font-size: 0.8rem;"><kbd>/acid info</kbd> - View information about the Acid Block you're looking at</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="tab-pane fade" id="bastion" role="tabpanel">
                        <div class="row">
                            <div class="col-sm">
                                <img src="/images/bastion.png" style="max-width: 100%;">
                                <h1 style="font-family: 'Archivo Black', sans-serif; margin: 0; padding: 0;">BASTION</h1>

                                <p style="margin: 0; padding: 0;">
                                    Bastions prevent players who are not in your network from fortifying blocks within a <b>16 block radius</b> of the block.
                                </p>

                                <br>

                                <p style="margin: 0; padding: 0;">
                                    Bastions <b>only</b> protect again blocks being fortified <b>above</b> it. This makes Bastions extremely vulnerable to being attacked
                                    from the side or below.
                                </p>

                                <br>

                                <p style="margin: 0; padding: 0;">
                                    Type <kbd>/bastion create &lt;network&gt;</kbd> while looking at a Sponge Block to create a new Bastion Block.
                                    Once the Bastion Block matures players that are not in the network will not be able to fortify blocks in that are in its range.
                                </p>

                                <br>

                                <p style="margin: 0; padding: 0;">
                                    To check if you're in a Bastion Field, type <kbd>/bastion near</kbd> to view a detailed list of all Bastions you are in the field of.
                                </p>
                            </div>

                            <div class="col-sm">
                                <div class="col-sm">
                                    <div class="embed-responsive embed-responsive-16by9">
                                        <iframe class="embed-responsive-item" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/VNvK1XcVIss" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>
                                    </div>

                                    <h5 style="margin-top: 8px;">Commands</h5>
                                    <p style="font-size: 0.8rem;"><kbd>/bastion create &lt;network&gt;</kbd> - Create a Bastion Block</p>
                                    <p style="font-size: 0.8rem;"><kbd>/bastion info</kbd> - View info for Bastion Block you're looking at</p>
                                    <p style="font-size: 0.8rem;"><kbd>/bastion near</kbd> - View a list of all Bastions you are in range of</p>
                                </div>
